## Per-file review

### `activegraph/scripts/gate_cli_flag_drift.py` (new)

- Module docstring cites the source amendments and the resolution
  coupling mechanism by hash. No hidden assumption between Spec and
  Code; D-2 footnote requirement satisfied.
- `_FLAG_LITERAL_RE` and `_DOC_FLAG_PATTERN` are anchored: the
  literal regex requires `^--<name>$`, the doc regex blocks trailing
  dashes by requiring an alphanumeric terminus. The `--supports-->`
  graph-arrow false-positive class is documented in the allowlist
  rather than swept under the regex; the test
  `test_extract_doc_flags_ignores_em_dashes_inside_words` covers the
  inverse case (intra-word `pre--post`).
- AST walker (`extract_cli_flags`) recognises `add_argument` /
  `option` / `Option` by function name only — robust to import
  aliasing (`from click import option`) and to multi-flag option
  decorators (`@option("-o", "--output-dir", ...)`). Covered by
  `test_extract_cli_flags_picks_up_click_option_with_short_first`.
- `__pycache__` filtering is explicit at the rglob level, not
  reliant on extension matching alone. Covered.
- Fail-closed clause is enforced at the boundary: `ast.parse` raises
  `SyntaxError`; we wrap it in `CliParseError` and `main()` returns
  exit code 2 (vs 1 for drift, 0 for clean). Three distinct exit
  codes give CI a way to distinguish parser-explosion from drift-
  found from clean.
- Allowlist loader is strict: `schema_version` must equal `"1"`,
  `flag` must start with `--`, `rationale` must be non-empty, and
  `expiry_date` is required. Optional `expiry_commit_ref` triggers
  the frame-status check when present. Every malformed case raises
  `AllowlistEntryMalformedError` at load time; no silent softening.
- `_frame_status_closed` searches both `repo_root/frames/` and
  `repo_root.parent/frames/` — handles the inner/outer split per
  the dark-factory convention. Test
  `test_resolved_entry_fails_closed` exercises this exact path with
  a synthetic `frames/t3-...status` file.

### `activegraph/cli_flag_drift_allowlist.toml` (new)

- Header doc-comment block names the gate file as the schema
  validator, the source amendment commits, and the three error
  classes raised on malformation. Schema is self-documenting to a
  reader who lands on the file cold.
- Each entry has a rationale that's specific (not "see other doc"),
  an `expiry_date`, and an explicit drift-class. The three classes
  in this initial allowlist —
  (a) t3-pending impl (`--set`/`--memo`/`--search`,
       expiry_commit_ref → frame:t3-implement-cli-set-flag),
  (b) documented-as-dropped (`--live`, CONTRACT v1.0 #C3),
  (c) cross-tool / placeholder / known-doc-drift (all others) —
  are visually grouped by comment headers. An auditor reading the
  file sees the suppression surface in one read.
- The `--out` ↔ `--output` symmetric pair is named honestly: the
  CLI registers `--output`, docs say `--out`, the gate would flag
  both directions, and the allowlist documents that pair as
  doc-update follow-up since docs/** are :ro in the t2 frame's
  perms. Not swept under a generic rationale.

### `activegraph/tests/test_cli_flag_drift.py` (modified — full rewrite)

- Synthetic fixtures live under `tmp_path` (per-test), not under
  a checked-in directory. This prevents the silent-fixture-drift
  failure mode and was the right call when the test owner's
  shipping version used a checked-in fixtures dir.
- The gate module is loaded via `importlib.util.spec_from_file_location`
  with explicit `sys.modules` registration (workaround for
  `@dataclass` in 3.14 needing the module dict). No `sys.path`
  pollution.
- The synthetic drift cases assert the gate **detected** the
  expected drift (`"--internal" in report.undocumented`), not the
  reverse "no drift" shape. This is the correct test discipline:
  every drift class is positively asserted, so a regression in the
  detection surface trips the test instead of silently passing.
- Real-corpus tests (`TestRealProjectFlagDiscovery`) run against
  the live CLI and live docs; the spot-check subset
  (`{"--run-id", "--tail", "--json", ...}`) is small enough to be
  stable across CLI additions but large enough that any
  catastrophic regression in the extractor would fail.
- `test_gate_main_exit_code_zero` exercises the `main()` exit
  surface end-to-end — predicate-8 + predicate-12 coverage in one
  test.

### `activegraph/.github/workflows/wheel-completeness.yml` (modified)

- `on.push.paths` expansion includes every doc-corpus source the
  gate scans (CHANGELOG/CONTRACT/README/HANDOFF/CONTRIBUTING and
  `docs/**`) plus the gate script + allowlist + test file. A
  doc-only PR that introduces drift triggers the gate; a code-only
  PR that adds a flag without documenting it triggers the gate.
- Two new steps run after the wheel-completeness step: pytest
  surface (`tests/test_cli_flag_drift.py -v`) and end-to-end gate
  script. Both must exit 0. Sequencing keeps the slow wheel build
  first; the drift gate adds <1s to the workflow.

